{
  "enabled": true,
  "name": "3 · EOD: System Refresh",
  "version": "5.1.0",
  "description": "Autoresearch loop: maintenance → cascade to all organs → up to 5 experiments.",
  "when": {
    "type": "userTriggered"
  },
  "then": {
    "type": "askAgent",
    "prompt": "Run the autoresearch loop. Protocol: ~/shared/context/body/heart.md. Read it first. These rules OVERRIDE heart.md defaults.\n\nCONTEXT LOAD (once):\n- ~/shared/context/body/heart.md (loop protocol)\n- ~/shared/context/changelog.md (what changed last run)\n- ~/shared/context/active/current.md (live state)\n\n=== PHASE 1: MAINTENANCE ===\nRefresh ground truth from email/calendar.\n- Read changelog.md FIRST. Skip substeps where target was updated <24h ago AND no new signals reference it.\n- Update current.md: new projects, people, meetings, pending action statuses. Bump date.\n- Update org-chart.md if org changes detected.\n\nSLACK INGESTION (substep within Phase 1 — not a new phase):\n1. Load ~/shared/context/active/slack-channel-registry.json and ~/shared/context/active/slack-scan-state.json.\n2. Scan all Tier 1 channels: retrieve messages since last scan timestamp using batch_get_conversation_history. For threads with >5 replies, retrieve full thread via batch_get_thread_replies.\n3. Scan Tier 2 channels: only if scan_interval_hours has elapsed since last scan for that channel.\n4. Scan DM conversations with People Watch contacts (from channel registry people_watch section).\n5. Run Relevance Filter on all retrieved messages (same scoring model as morning routine — direct mention +100, manager +100, People Watch boosted +30, active project keyword +25, keyword trigger +20, Tier 1 channel +15, decision language +20, action assignment +25, deadline +15, escalation +20, hot topic +15, thread >5 replies +10; threshold: 25 points). Extract Signals from messages scoring >= 25.\n6. If signals found: produce ~/shared/context/intake/slack-digest-{YYYY-MM-DD-HHmm}.md (500 word cap, ranked by relevance score, [ACTION-RW] prefix for Richard's action items).\n7. Update ~/shared/context/active/slack-scan-state.json: last_scan timestamp, per-channel last_message_ts, signals_extracted counts, and tool_invocation_log entries for audit.\n8. On rate limit or API error: log the error to scan state, continue with other data sources. Do not fail the loop.\nNote: The Slack digest in intake/ gets processed by the existing 'Process intake/ using gut.md Digestion Protocol' substep below — no separate processing needed.\n\n- Process intake/ using gut.md Digestion Protocol — extract facts into organs, archive processed files, delete transient files.\n- Review soul.md — suggest changes if role/preferences shifted (don't auto-edit).\n- Log all changes to changelog.md.\n\n=== PHASE 2: CASCADE TO ALL ORGANS ===\nPropagate Phase 1 changes. Read each organ, update only stale sections.\n- Eyes: refresh predicted QA (only topics with new signals). Update metrics/competitors if new data.\n- Memory: update relationship graph (only contacts in recent email). Update compressed context if projects changed. Do NOT update meeting briefs — those live in ~/shared/context/meetings/ now. If meetings/ series files have new open items that affect relationship context, update the relationship entry's 'Current topic' line only.\n- Hands: update action tracker (new tasks, completed, blockers, signals). Update overdue list.\n- Brain: add new decisions if made. Update Five Levels status if progress detected.\n- Spine: update system history if structural changes.\n- Nervous System: update delegation scorecard. Flag overdue calibration loops. On Fridays, generate weekly calibration report.\n- aMCC: update streak (did Richard do the hard thing since last run?). Rotate hard thing if previous one was completed or is now blocked. Update resistance taxonomy if new patterns observed.\n- Device: update delegation protocol statuses. Update tool factory if new automation opportunities surfaced.\n- Gut: AFTER all other organs updated, check each organ's word count against budget (see gut.md). Flag any over budget. Run bloat detection signals. Report gut health.\n- SKIP rule: if organ section updated <48h ago and upstream change is minor (single fact, not structural), skip.\n- ALWAYS cascade to Memory compressed context if current.md had structural changes.\n\nSLACK SIGNAL ROUTING (during Phase 2 cascade):\nWhen processing Slack digests from intake/, route each Signal to organs based on type:\n- decision → brain.md (decision log entry with source attribution) + current.md\n- action-item → hands.md (new action item with [Slack] source tag) + current.md (pending actions)\n- status-change → current.md (updated project status line) + eyes.md (if metric-related)\n- escalation → current.md (escalation note on relevant project) + hands.md (if Richard needs to act)\n- mention → current.md (context note, only if substantive)\n- topic-update → current.md (hot topic summary) + brain.md (if strategic)\n- Relationship info (tone shift, new person) → memory.md (updated relationship graph entry)\n- Market metrics / competitive intel → eyes.md (updated metrics or competitor note)\nConstraints:\n- No new organ files created — all Slack signals absorbed into existing organs.\n- Before writing Slack-sourced content to an organ, check its word budget in gut.md. If at capacity, compress existing content first or defer the signal to the next cycle.\n- Source attribution: every Slack-sourced fact written to an organ MUST include [Slack: #channel, author, date] tag for provenance.\n- After routing all signals from a digest, delete the processed digest file from intake/.\n\nVOLUME CONTROL & HOT TOPIC DETECTION (applies during Phase 1 ingestion and Phase 2 cascade):\nWeekly cumulative tracking:\n- After each organ write from Slack-sourced content, update volume_tracking.words_by_organ in slack-scan-state.json.\n- Week resets on Monday (aligned with week_start field).\n20% ceiling rule:\n- If cumulative Slack-sourced words for any organ exceed 20% of that organ's word budget (per gut.md) in a single week, reduce scan frequency for channels feeding that organ: Tier 1 channels scan every other cycle, Tier 2 channels skip until next week.\n- Log the throttle in scan state. Resume normal frequency on weekly reset.\n- Budget reference: Memory 3500w (700w ceiling), Brain 2500w (500w), Eyes 2500w (500w), Hands 2000w (400w), current.md flag if >500w/week.\nHot topic detection:\n- When the same topic appears in Signals from 3+ distinct channels within a 24-hour window, flag as hot topic in slack-scan-state.json hot_topics.active (with topic name, first_seen, channels list, key_participants, signal_count).\n- Include hot topic summary in the Slack Digest. Boost relevance score +15 for all messages in the topic cluster (+25 if topic relates to an active project in current.md).\nHot topic cooling:\n- If a hot topic has no new Signals for 48 hours, move from hot_topics.active to hot_topics.cooled. Stop applying relevance boost. Remove from digest hot topics section.\nPeople Watch derivation:\n- During Phase 2 cascade, after memory.md is updated, re-derive the people_watch section in slack-channel-registry.json from memory.md's Relationship Graph.\n- always_high_relevance: Richard's direct manager (Brandon). boosted: all Relationship Graph entries with interaction in last 60 days. Dormant contacts (60+ days): excluded until they resurface.\n- Record last_derived timestamp in the channel registry.\nNew person detection:\n- Track unique Slack users in conversations with Richard (DMs or @mentions). If a user not in People Watch appears 3+ times in a 7-day window, add to people_watch_candidates in scan state.\nDM monitoring:\n- Scan Richard's DM conversations with People Watch contacts. Extract signals using the same Relevance Filter. Respect read-only guardrails (see slack-guardrails.md).\n\n=== GATE: EXPERIMENT DECISION ===\n- ALWAYS run Phase 3 — experiments are generated at runtime, there is no queue to be empty.\n- Karpathy's per-organ cooldown (heart.md) excludes organs modified by maintenance in this invocation.\n\n=== PHASE 3: UP TO 5 EXPERIMENTS (Karpathy-governed) ===\nExperiments are governed by the Karpathy agent (see soul.md Agent Routing Directory). Route experiment execution through Karpathy. The full experiment protocol — including orchestrated blind evaluation — lives in heart.md Steps 1-6. Reference heart.md as the source of truth; do not duplicate the protocol here.\n\nORCHESTRATION ARCHITECTURE (4-step sequential):\n1. Main loop invokes Karpathy → selects target, snapshots, applies experiment, generates 5 eval questions + ground truth answers. Returns modified file + questions + ground truth.\n2. Main loop invokes Evaluator A (Amazon-context) → receives modified file + body.md + soul.md + questions. Just answers. No scoring.\n3. Main loop invokes Evaluator B (Generic) → receives ONLY modified file + questions. Just answers. No scoring.\n4. Main loop invokes Karpathy again → receives both evaluators' answers + ground truth. Karpathy scores and makes KEEP/REVERT decision.\nKey: evaluators are witnesses (answer only), Karpathy is judge (scores + decides). Neither evaluator knows what changed or that the other exists.\n\nBATCH RULES:\n- Run up to 5 experiments per invocation.\n- Stop on 3 consecutive reverts (diminishing returns).\n- Most experiments will revert. That's expected.\n- Log each experiment as one line: [organ:section] TECHNIQUE → Xw→Yw. A=X/5 B=X/5. KEEP/REVERT.\n\nDO-NO-HARM RULES (non-negotiable):\n- SNAPSHOT: cp target_organ.md target_organ.bak BEFORE any edit.\n- Quality threshold is ORGAN-SPECIFIC:\n  Brain (decisions, principles): 100% accuracy required. Zero tolerance for wrong answers.\n  Memory (relationships, meeting briefs): 100% accuracy required. Wrong tone/relationship data = bad emails.\n  Eyes (metrics, competitors): 95% accuracy. Directional data can have minor imprecision.\n  Hands (tasks, status): 95% accuracy. Task status must be correct.\n  All other organs: 90% accuracy minimum.\n- WORD BUDGET: If the experiment would push the organ over its word budget (see gut.md), the experiment must ALSO compress existing content to stay within budget.\n\nEXPERIMENT PROTOCOL:\n1. Karpathy generates experiment at runtime: picks organ (weighted: over-budget → staleness → random), section (random), technique (random).\n2. Follow heart.md Steps 1-6 (Select Target → Snapshot → Apply → Orchestrated Blind Eval → Keep/Revert → Repeat).\n3. Evaluation uses orchestrated blind eval (heart.md Steps 4-5): 4-step sequential — Karpathy (experiment + questions + ground truth) → Eval A (Amazon-context, answers only) → Eval B (generic, answers only) → Karpathy (scores + decides). Both evaluators must score ≥4/5 to KEEP.\n4. If any do-no-harm rule or eval threshold fails: RESET. Restore from .bak. Log why.\n5. Log result to changelog.md (one line per experiment).\n6. Repeat up to 5 experiments. Stop on 3 consecutive reverts.\n\n=== PHASE 4: SUGGESTED CHANGES ===\nPresent up to 3 suggestions to Richard. Each suggestion MUST:\n- Connect to a specific goal in brain.md (Five Levels) or a calibration finding in nervous-system.md\n- Be measurable (what metric improves, by how much, over what timeframe)\n- Be reversible (can be undone if it doesn't work)\n- NOT modify soul.md or steering files without Richard's explicit approval\n- NOT restructure organs (that's a deliberate architecture decision, not a suggestion)\n\nFormat:\n1. [TITLE] — [description]. Why: [goal/calibration connection]. Measure: [what metric, target, timeframe]. Reversible: [how to undo]. Risk: [what could go wrong]. → Approve/Deny?\n\nIf fewer than 3 suggestions meet these criteria, present fewer. Quality over quantity.\n\n=== PHASE 5: CONCLUSION ===\n1-2 sentences: what changed, expected impact, forward look.\n\n=== REPORT ===\n1. Maintenance: what changed\n2. Cascade: which organs updated (list all 11), gut health (word counts, bloat signals)\n3. aMCC: streak update, hard thing status\n4. Experiment: which ran (or why skipped), ADVANCE/RESET/SKIPPED, word count delta, accuracy scores\n5. Suggestions: what was proposed (or why fewer than 3)\n6. Next run: next experiment in queue, organs approaching staleness, calibration loops due\n\n=== SELF-AUDIT (run last, every time) ===\nBefore logging to changelog, verify:\n1. CASCADE COMPLETENESS: List every organ in the body (brain, eyes, hands, memory, spine, nervous-system, amcc, device, gut). For each: was it checked during Phase 2? If skipped, was the skip rule applied correctly (updated <48h + minor change)? If an organ was neither updated nor explicitly skipped, flag it as a MISSED CASCADE.\n2. STRUCTURAL CHANGE CHECK: Did this run create, rename, move, or delete any file? If yes, run the Structural Change Protocol from nervous-system.md — check that body.md, soul.md, spine.md, heart.md, and all hooks were updated.\n3. COHERENCE SPOT-CHECK: Pick 2 random cross-references from the files you touched (e.g., a path in soul.md, a hook cascade target). Verify they point to files that exist and contain what they claim. If any are broken, fix immediately.\n\nLog self-audit results in the report. Format:\nSELF-AUDIT: Cascade [X]/9 organs covered. Structural changes: [yes/no]. Coherence spot-check: [X]/2 valid.\n\nLog to ~/shared/context/changelog.md.\n\n=== PHASE 6: HOUSEKEEPING & GIT SYNC ===\nBefore pushing, deduplicate the MCP autoApprove lists in ~/.kiro/settings/mcp.json. Run: python3 -c \"import json; f='$HOME/.kiro/settings/mcp.json'; d=json.load(open(f)); [srv.__setitem__('autoApprove', list(dict.fromkeys(srv.get('autoApprove',[])))) for srv in d.get('mcpServers',{}).values()]; json.dump(d, open(f,'w'), indent=2)\"\nThen run: ~/shared/tools/git-sync/sync.sh push\nThis pushes all changes to the personal GitHub repo so the local machine stays in sync. Silent if nothing changed. Do not skip this step."
  }
}
